WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.006 --> 00:00:08.925
[birds chirping]

2
00:00:13.013 --> 00:00:15.015
[soft music playing]

3
00:00:18.351 --> 00:00:19.352
[Charles] <i>Dear Father.</i>

4
00:00:19.978 --> 00:00:23.398
<i>I've been thinking of you.
how much you'd love the skies here.</i>

5
00:00:24.149 --> 00:00:26.192
<i>I remember sitting with you
when I was small.</i>

6
00:00:26.693 --> 00:00:29.612
<i>We'd look up at the clouds
and imagine all the secrets they knew.</i>

7
00:00:30.864 --> 00:00:33.092
<i>You'd be happy to know
your granddaughters are thriving here.</i>

8
00:00:33.116 --> 00:00:34.301
[Laura] "And Faria gave him…"

9
00:00:34.325 --> 00:00:36.804
[Charles] <i>Laura's found a love
for the prairie and for reading.</i>

10
00:00:36.828 --> 00:00:38.180
"…should recover the treasure."

11
00:00:38.204 --> 00:00:41.374
[Charles] <i>It's nothing to do with us.
but the good influence of her new friend.</i>

12
00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:44.753
<i>Mary inherited Mother's skill
with the needle.</i>

13
00:00:45.420 --> 00:00:48.173
<i>She's now requesting thread
as a gift instead of candy.</i>

14
00:00:49.424 --> 00:00:50.884
<i>Caroline is happy here.</i>

15
00:00:51.468 --> 00:00:54.220
<i>She's found a wide circle
of friends and acquaintances.</i>

16
00:00:55.805 --> 00:00:58.075
<i>The corn is growing strong and steady.</i>

17
00:00:58.099 --> 00:00:59.934
<i>Land office should open any day now.</i>

18
00:01:00.435 --> 00:01:02.812
<i>and our future here
will be finally settled.</i>

19
00:01:03.313 --> 00:01:06.107
<i>Most importantly.
you have a new granddaughter.</i>

20
00:01:06.816 --> 00:01:08.026
<i>We call her Carrie.</i>

21
00:01:08.526 --> 00:01:10.504
<i>She's healthy and perfect.</i>

22
00:01:10.528 --> 00:01:13.198
<i>Every time I look at her.
I feel overwhelmed with love.</i>

23
00:01:13.698 --> 00:01:15.658
<i>the same love I know you had for me</i>

24
00:01:16.284 --> 00:01:17.410
<i>and for George.</i>

25
00:01:19.454 --> 00:01:21.206
<i>I'm sorry for how we left things.</i>

26
00:01:21.790 --> 00:01:24.167
<i>I hope you can find it
in your heart to forgive me.</i>

27
00:01:24.667 --> 00:01:25.667
<i>If not.</i>

28
00:01:26.252 --> 00:01:28.338
<i>please know that we are happy
on the prairie.</i>

29
00:01:29.839 --> 00:01:31.966
<i>happy in our new home.</i>

30
00:01:37.555 --> 00:01:38.555
Pa.

31
00:01:39.682 --> 00:01:40.683
Look.

32
00:01:41.768 --> 00:01:43.770
[hooves clopping]

33
00:01:45.730 --> 00:01:47.732
[horses whinny]

34
00:01:55.949 --> 00:01:57.109
[Laura] Where are they going?

35
00:01:58.326 --> 00:01:59.494
The chiefs are gathering.

36
00:02:00.662 --> 00:02:03.373
Mr. Mitchell said
they're finally ready to sign the treaty.

37
00:02:05.208 --> 00:02:06.584
Then what happens?

38
00:02:08.086 --> 00:02:09.504
They move to Indian territory.

39
00:02:15.510 --> 00:02:16.510
[Laura] All of them?

40
00:02:17.220 --> 00:02:18.513
Even Good Eagle?

41
00:02:27.021 --> 00:02:29.941
Come on.
We got the reverend's welcome lunch today.

42
00:02:30.441 --> 00:02:32.503
And I can't wait
to eat all your ma's cobblers.

43
00:02:32.527 --> 00:02:35.214
-You just finished breakfast.
-I like to plan ahead.

44
00:02:35.238 --> 00:02:36.257
[Mary chuckles softly]

45
00:02:36.281 --> 00:02:37.281
All right.

46
00:02:37.615 --> 00:02:39.617
[melancholy music playing]

47
00:02:55.550 --> 00:02:56.777
[music fades]

48
00:02:56.801 --> 00:02:58.320
[kitten purring]

49
00:02:58.344 --> 00:03:01.431
[in Osage] Hold still. Enough with Potato.

50
00:03:03.850 --> 00:03:05.643
[footsteps approaching]

51
00:03:06.603 --> 00:03:08.914
[in English] Sure you wanna spend
your birthday with Laura?

52
00:03:08.938 --> 00:03:11.138
[Good Eagle] You're busy.
And she has a surprise for me.

53
00:03:11.941 --> 00:03:14.336
You look nice and important.

54
00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:15.588
I agree.

55
00:03:15.612 --> 00:03:16.881
We'll celebrate tonight…

56
00:03:16.905 --> 00:03:18.048
-Hm.
-[wagon approaching]

57
00:03:18.072 --> 00:03:19.616
…when everything is settled.

58
00:03:20.325 --> 00:03:23.262
-[Laura] Good Eagle! Come on!
-Remember what we told you.

59
00:03:23.286 --> 00:03:26.182
Be alert. Pay attention
to everything going on around you.

60
00:03:26.206 --> 00:03:27.975
I'll be there to pick you up
this afternoon.

61
00:03:27.999 --> 00:03:31.085
I will. And I definitely didn't look
at all the presents you got me.

62
00:03:31.586 --> 00:03:32.897
Okay. bye. Good luck.

63
00:03:32.921 --> 00:03:33.856
[footsteps receding]

64
00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:37.026
-She definitely looked at them.
-[door opens. closes]

65
00:03:37.050 --> 00:03:41.346
And she forgot her <i>ha-xin.</i>
That child. She takes after you.

66
00:03:41.971 --> 00:03:43.973
[wagon receding]

67
00:03:45.058 --> 00:03:46.226
Are you nervous?

68
00:03:46.851 --> 00:03:49.455
No. I've done plenty of translating.

69
00:03:49.479 --> 00:03:51.272
The chiefs need someone like you.

70
00:03:51.773 --> 00:03:54.627
someone to tell them
exactly what those people are saying.

71
00:03:54.651 --> 00:03:57.237
They trust you because they know you.

72
00:03:58.446 --> 00:04:00.657
I just wanna be sure
we're doing the right thing.

73
00:04:01.824 --> 00:04:03.701
[sighs] It's the only thing.

74
00:04:04.786 --> 00:04:06.496
I wish it weren't true. but…

75
00:04:08.623 --> 00:04:09.623
Here we are.

76
00:04:10.375 --> 00:04:11.751
[chickens clucking]

77
00:04:13.711 --> 00:04:14.796
Here we are.

78
00:04:25.390 --> 00:04:28.410
-[indistinct chatter]
-[distant repetitive pounding]

79
00:04:28.434 --> 00:04:30.186
-[Laura giggles]
-What's that sound?

80
00:04:31.312 --> 00:04:33.749
Drums. to tell the men
to gather for the council.

81
00:04:33.773 --> 00:04:35.858
If the chiefs sign.
will you have to leave?

82
00:04:36.734 --> 00:04:39.737
What if the chiefs don't sign?
Will we have to leave?

83
00:04:40.446 --> 00:04:41.382
I don't know.

84
00:04:41.406 --> 00:04:43.842
[Caroline] All right.
enough with the questions.

85
00:04:43.866 --> 00:04:45.302
It's Good Eagle's birthday.

86
00:04:45.326 --> 00:04:48.097
-Laura. why don't you tell her the plan?
-Tell me the plan.

87
00:04:48.121 --> 00:04:50.123
We have a chore to do.

88
00:04:51.416 --> 00:04:52.309
A chore?

89
00:04:52.333 --> 00:04:54.460
We have to mail this letter.

90
00:04:55.670 --> 00:04:57.022
Come on. let's go!

91
00:04:57.046 --> 00:04:58.089
[wagon approaching]

92
00:04:58.965 --> 00:05:00.216
Ingalls!

93
00:05:01.301 --> 00:05:02.301
You hear that?

94
00:05:03.261 --> 00:05:05.698
This is what we've all been waiting for.

95
00:05:05.722 --> 00:05:08.725
Care to come with me
and witness history in the making?

96
00:05:09.309 --> 00:05:10.310
To the council?

97
00:05:11.602 --> 00:05:14.123
I didn't realize
it was open to the public.

98
00:05:14.147 --> 00:05:17.376
Well. it's our future
just as much as theirs. [chuckles]

99
00:05:17.400 --> 00:05:19.837
Come on. The deal's done.

100
00:05:19.861 --> 00:05:21.487
It's all for show now.

101
00:05:21.988 --> 00:05:25.759
It's a short ride. and we'll be back
before the reverend finishes grace.

102
00:05:25.783 --> 00:05:26.783
I promise.

103
00:05:27.452 --> 00:05:29.078
It's history in the making.

104
00:05:29.579 --> 00:05:30.723
[lighthearted music playing]

105
00:05:30.747 --> 00:05:31.998
Save me some cobbler.

106
00:05:33.207 --> 00:05:34.207
[Eli chuckles]

107
00:05:34.959 --> 00:05:36.895
That's the spirit. Ingalls.

108
00:05:36.919 --> 00:05:38.338
-[chuckles]
-[driver cues horses]

109
00:05:43.301 --> 00:05:44.469
Just us. then.

110
00:05:53.603 --> 00:05:57.106
Doesn't look very welcoming
for a welcome luncheon.

111
00:05:57.815 --> 00:05:59.043
No. it doesn't.

112
00:05:59.067 --> 00:06:01.128
[Carrie cooing]

113
00:06:01.152 --> 00:06:02.046
[Caroline] Margaret.

114
00:06:02.070 --> 00:06:03.005
[music fades]

115
00:06:03.029 --> 00:06:04.089
Can I help?

116
00:06:04.113 --> 00:06:06.216
Caroline. Jemma left me in charge.

117
00:06:06.240 --> 00:06:09.261
She promised she'd provide everything.
but there's nothing here.

118
00:06:09.285 --> 00:06:12.181
There's no tables
or chairs or plates or cups.

119
00:06:12.205 --> 00:06:14.600
Weren't we meant
to bring our own plates and cups?

120
00:06:14.624 --> 00:06:17.311
I don't know. I told her
I wasn't good at these sort of things.

121
00:06:17.335 --> 00:06:21.523
but she said that I needed to step up
and that surely I was clever enough.

122
00:06:21.547 --> 00:06:23.734
but I am not at all.

123
00:06:23.758 --> 00:06:25.218
I am not clever.

124
00:06:26.010 --> 00:06:28.290
-It's all right. We'll figure things out.
-[Carrie coos]

125
00:06:29.180 --> 00:06:31.182
[mellow music playing]

126
00:06:31.724 --> 00:06:32.850
Ladies.

127
00:06:34.060 --> 00:06:37.498
Uh. let's… let's carry out the benches
from the church for seating.

128
00:06:37.522 --> 00:06:39.083
And. um. Sarah.

129
00:06:39.107 --> 00:06:42.610
run down to the mill and ask them
to bring over some planks for tables.

130
00:06:43.111 --> 00:06:45.589
We'll use the sawhorses for legs.

131
00:06:45.613 --> 00:06:49.385
Can you go see if Miss Henderson has
anything to use for tablecloths and vases?

132
00:06:49.409 --> 00:06:50.535
Yes. Ma.

133
00:06:52.870 --> 00:06:55.373
-Let's get those benches.
-Yes. ma'am.

134
00:06:59.001 --> 00:07:00.420
[bell dings]

135
00:07:05.049 --> 00:07:06.068
[music fades]

136
00:07:06.092 --> 00:07:07.277
Hello.

137
00:07:07.301 --> 00:07:10.054
Hello. Mr. Henry.
I'd like to mail this letter.

138
00:07:10.638 --> 00:07:11.698
Very good.

139
00:07:11.722 --> 00:07:15.768
And also to ask if you've got
any letters for Good Eagle Mitchell

140
00:07:16.269 --> 00:07:17.746
because today is her birthday.

141
00:07:17.770 --> 00:07:19.814
As a matter of fact.

142
00:07:20.731 --> 00:07:22.900
I think something
came in just this morning.

143
00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:32.200
Open it.

144
00:07:37.415 --> 00:07:38.767
[Good Eagle] It's a treasure map.

145
00:07:38.791 --> 00:07:42.378
The Count of Monte Cristo
must have hidden treasure in Independence.

146
00:07:42.920 --> 00:07:44.046
Where does it say to go?

147
00:07:44.547 --> 00:07:48.068
We're here. and the first treasure's here.

148
00:07:48.092 --> 00:07:49.719
That's the Judson Hotel.

149
00:07:50.887 --> 00:07:51.947
Come on!

150
00:07:51.971 --> 00:07:53.615
Thanks. Mr. Henry.

151
00:07:53.639 --> 00:07:55.701
[upbeat music playing]

152
00:07:55.725 --> 00:07:57.727
[indistinct chatter]

153
00:08:07.904 --> 00:08:09.780
[chatter in Osage]

154
00:08:13.910 --> 00:08:14.910
[Eli clears throat]

155
00:08:16.078 --> 00:08:17.246
[in English] Nice to see you.

156
00:08:19.916 --> 00:08:20.958
It's good to see ya.

157
00:08:23.044 --> 00:08:24.879
Didn't expect to see you here.

158
00:08:25.379 --> 00:08:27.423
I thought I'd show my respect.

159
00:08:28.466 --> 00:08:30.676
Hate to see good people lose so much.

160
00:08:31.177 --> 00:08:32.762
Eli says it's a good deal.

161
00:08:34.013 --> 00:08:35.157
fair for everyone.

162
00:08:35.181 --> 00:08:37.183
Ah. that depends on
your definition of fair.

163
00:08:38.643 --> 00:08:39.727
[Eli] Ingalls!

164
00:08:40.353 --> 00:08:42.748
I'd like you to meet
Indian Agent Isaac Gibson.

165
00:08:42.772 --> 00:08:46.752
the man we hope
will talk some sense into the seven chiefs

166
00:08:46.776 --> 00:08:48.945
of the seven bands who gather here today.

167
00:08:49.737 --> 00:08:54.092
Agent Gibson. Charles Ingalls
is one of our finest homesteaders.

168
00:08:54.116 --> 00:08:56.553
He has a beautiful wife.
three lovely girls.

169
00:08:56.577 --> 00:08:58.996
and a true passion for this land.

170
00:08:59.705 --> 00:09:03.668
Help me. Mr. Ingalls. What brought you
to this land you have such a passion for?

171
00:09:05.169 --> 00:09:07.213
Same thing as most men. I guess.

172
00:09:08.089 --> 00:09:10.591
The open skies. a new life.

173
00:09:11.425 --> 00:09:13.570
a fresh start for my family.

174
00:09:13.594 --> 00:09:16.365
But why here?
Why this little piece of Kansas?

175
00:09:16.389 --> 00:09:19.183
Why come to a place so unavailable?

176
00:09:20.309 --> 00:09:21.936
To be honest. it was a flyer.

177
00:09:22.436 --> 00:09:23.896
Saw them all over Lake Pepin.

178
00:09:24.397 --> 00:09:26.649
Let me guess. "Free land in the West"?

179
00:09:27.358 --> 00:09:30.254
"Millions of acres"?
"Pure and abundant water"?

180
00:09:30.278 --> 00:09:32.089
[mellow music playing]

181
00:09:32.113 --> 00:09:33.197
[Eli] Hm.

182
00:09:33.906 --> 00:09:34.949
Something like that.

183
00:09:35.449 --> 00:09:38.744
Well. he's here now.
That's the important thing.

184
00:09:39.328 --> 00:09:41.163
We're all here now.

185
00:09:42.373 --> 00:09:43.374
That's very true.

186
00:09:44.667 --> 00:09:45.710
Gentlemen.

187
00:09:49.380 --> 00:09:50.423
Ah.

188
00:09:51.382 --> 00:09:53.384
[indistinct chatter]

189
00:09:55.720 --> 00:09:56.822
[music fades]

190
00:09:56.846 --> 00:10:01.743
Uh. yeah. with that table.
And then we'll put the food on that.

191
00:10:01.767 --> 00:10:06.206
I don't know how she does that.
make everyone listen while she smiles.

192
00:10:06.230 --> 00:10:09.251
-It might be witchcraft.
-My mother's not a witch.

193
00:10:09.275 --> 00:10:12.069
-She's teasing.
-I'm saying it's impressive.

194
00:10:12.570 --> 00:10:15.781
Maybe you'll have that power too.
the power to enchant.

195
00:10:16.282 --> 00:10:17.282
Perfect!

196
00:10:17.742 --> 00:10:19.970
Thank you. You're all wonderful.

197
00:10:19.994 --> 00:10:21.305
-[Carrie fusses]
-Aw.

198
00:10:21.329 --> 00:10:24.600
[scoffs] She won't sleep.
She doesn't wanna miss any of the action.

199
00:10:24.624 --> 00:10:27.102
Well. Mary could take her
to the store where it's quiet.

200
00:10:27.126 --> 00:10:28.729
Caleb could use the company.

201
00:10:28.753 --> 00:10:29.730
[Mary chuckles]

202
00:10:29.754 --> 00:10:31.773
Go on. We'll save you some lunch.

203
00:10:31.797 --> 00:10:33.817
[heartwarming music playing]

204
00:10:33.841 --> 00:10:35.885
[Carrie fusses]

205
00:10:37.511 --> 00:10:39.615
I guess I knew that was happening.

206
00:10:39.639 --> 00:10:41.140
[women giggle]

207
00:10:43.309 --> 00:10:44.494
[music fades]

208
00:10:44.518 --> 00:10:46.121
[Russell] Where's Miss Henderson?

209
00:10:46.145 --> 00:10:48.314
Uh. she… she's over at the church.

210
00:10:51.067 --> 00:10:53.253
-Hi.
-[metal clangs]

211
00:10:53.277 --> 00:10:56.923
What is wrong with you. boy?
Don't you know how to work a scale?

212
00:10:56.947 --> 00:10:59.009
How someone could leave a kid

213
00:10:59.033 --> 00:11:01.702
as dull as an ox
to work the counter is beyond me.

214
00:11:02.745 --> 00:11:03.745
Well?

215
00:11:04.789 --> 00:11:06.123
Son. I ain't getting any younger.

216
00:11:10.419 --> 00:11:13.506
[Mary] It's nice to see you. Mr. Kind.
Let me help.

217
00:11:21.180 --> 00:11:23.659
-It'll be 15 cents.
-Well. that doesn't seem right.

218
00:11:23.683 --> 00:11:25.327
[Mary] This is a very nice cheese.

219
00:11:25.351 --> 00:11:27.996
I'm sure you're heading
to the reverend's luncheon with it.

220
00:11:28.020 --> 00:11:31.607
It's very generous of you.
Would you like me to add anything else?

221
00:11:32.191 --> 00:11:34.860
Just the cheese. Put it on my credit.

222
00:11:40.157 --> 00:11:41.157
[door closes]

223
00:11:41.867 --> 00:11:43.119
[both laugh]

224
00:11:48.999 --> 00:11:51.752
-Thank you.
-It's fun. I like playing shop.

225
00:11:52.336 --> 00:11:54.630
-I'll mark it in the ledger.
-Okay.

226
00:11:55.214 --> 00:11:56.340
I'll be right back.

227
00:12:03.222 --> 00:12:04.765
[melancholy music playing]

228
00:12:23.451 --> 00:12:24.553
[indistinct chatter]

229
00:12:24.577 --> 00:12:25.804
Hello. Hello.

230
00:12:25.828 --> 00:12:27.246
-[Emily] Oh!
-Sorry I'm late.

231
00:12:27.747 --> 00:12:30.475
The Sorenson boy
stuck his hand in a beehive.

232
00:12:30.499 --> 00:12:33.335
I had to pull eight stingers
out of his sticky little paws.

233
00:12:33.836 --> 00:12:37.232
Luckily. he's got quite a bit of meat
on those bones. so he'll be just fine.

234
00:12:37.256 --> 00:12:38.275
I'm glad to hear it.

235
00:12:38.299 --> 00:12:40.068
Mrs. Sorenson needs to tend to him.

236
00:12:40.092 --> 00:12:42.696
but she sent biscuits
and honeycomb in her place.

237
00:12:42.720 --> 00:12:45.389
-Oh. you can set them down over there.
-All right.

238
00:12:46.223 --> 00:12:48.285
-[birds chirping]
-[indistinct chatter continues]

239
00:12:48.309 --> 00:12:49.309
[chuckles]

240
00:12:49.769 --> 00:12:51.437
[laughing] What?

241
00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:56.334
If you think everyone doesn't know that
you've been having supper twice a week.

242
00:12:56.358 --> 00:12:57.335
you'd be wrong.

243
00:12:57.359 --> 00:12:58.694
Well. that's not true.

244
00:12:59.612 --> 00:13:01.548
-It's three times a week.
-[gasps playfully]

245
00:13:01.572 --> 00:13:02.841
[Emily laughs]

246
00:13:02.865 --> 00:13:05.576
-Are you going to marry him or not?
-Lacey.

247
00:13:06.702 --> 00:13:08.412
Three suppers a week?

248
00:13:08.913 --> 00:13:12.058
And a walk on Saturday mornings
before the store opens?

249
00:13:12.082 --> 00:13:13.793
-Hm.
-Yes. I know about that too.

250
00:13:14.752 --> 00:13:16.253
We haven't talked about it.

251
00:13:17.880 --> 00:13:19.983
We're stuck. I think.

252
00:13:20.007 --> 00:13:21.717
Or he's stuck. I don't know.

253
00:13:23.594 --> 00:13:27.890
We talk about everything under the sun.
but he just won't bring up the future.

254
00:13:28.474 --> 00:13:29.701
Maybe you ask him.

255
00:13:29.725 --> 00:13:31.286
-[laughs]
<i>-Pourquoi?</i>

256
00:13:31.310 --> 00:13:34.039
Is that shocking? Did I offend you?

257
00:13:34.063 --> 00:13:36.416
I just thought
you didn't believe in marriage.

258
00:13:36.440 --> 00:13:40.486
No. I believe in marriage
for other people.

259
00:13:40.986 --> 00:13:44.240
-I've already had mine.
-I've been as clear as I can be.

260
00:13:46.075 --> 00:13:47.075
Are you sure?

261
00:13:48.118 --> 00:13:50.704
Life can get away from you
if you don't speak your heart.

262
00:13:51.372 --> 00:13:53.290
If I've learned anything here. it's that.

263
00:13:53.874 --> 00:13:55.459
[heartwarming music playing]

264
00:13:56.669 --> 00:13:58.212
I'm going to go get more water.

265
00:14:05.553 --> 00:14:06.720
…and then some.

266
00:14:10.182 --> 00:14:11.182
[chuckles]

267
00:14:23.112 --> 00:14:25.114
[both giggling]

268
00:14:30.953 --> 00:14:32.514
[Good Eagle] Ooh…

269
00:14:32.538 --> 00:14:35.249
You must share in my treasure.
Monsieur Morrel.

270
00:14:43.382 --> 00:14:44.925
Do you want to move away?

271
00:14:45.926 --> 00:14:48.321
-Pop says we don't have to move.
-[music fades]

272
00:14:48.345 --> 00:14:50.615
We could stay
on the farm like Cousin Louis.

273
00:14:50.639 --> 00:14:53.058
but the rest
of my family would have to go.

274
00:14:54.101 --> 00:14:55.311
And I'd miss them.

275
00:14:57.813 --> 00:15:00.190
When I came here from the Big Woods.

276
00:15:01.734 --> 00:15:07.323
I missed my grandma and grandpa
and aunts and uncles and cousins so much.

277
00:15:08.532 --> 00:15:11.035
I felt like I was being pulled in half.

278
00:15:13.579 --> 00:15:15.748
Now I can't imagine going back.

279
00:15:18.208 --> 00:15:20.753
But I also can't imagine it here
without you.

280
00:15:22.212 --> 00:15:23.815
It's not my decision.

281
00:15:23.839 --> 00:15:25.841
[melancholy music playing]

282
00:15:26.967 --> 00:15:28.010
I'm sorry.

283
00:15:29.136 --> 00:15:30.304
It's your birthday.

284
00:15:31.013 --> 00:15:33.390
and we should only talk about fun things.

285
00:15:34.391 --> 00:15:36.018
So where's next?

286
00:15:37.811 --> 00:15:39.229
[Good Eagle] The alley.

287
00:15:45.069 --> 00:15:47.339
-[horses neighing]
-[music fades]

288
00:15:47.363 --> 00:15:49.883
[indistinct chatter in Osage]

289
00:15:49.907 --> 00:15:51.909
[tense music playing]

290
00:15:59.041 --> 00:16:00.041
Who's that?

291
00:16:00.542 --> 00:16:01.835
I saw him riding in.

292
00:16:03.087 --> 00:16:07.007
His name is Joseph Pawnee-no-pashe.
They call him Governor Joe.

293
00:16:07.841 --> 00:16:09.361
[Charles] Why Governor and not Chief?

294
00:16:09.385 --> 00:16:10.695
Word is he took the title

295
00:16:10.719 --> 00:16:13.514
'cause he wanted the Indian agents
to think he was reasonable.

296
00:16:14.682 --> 00:16:17.559
Word also is
he is the smartest man in this lodge.

297
00:16:27.236 --> 00:16:28.338
[Isaac clears throat]

298
00:16:28.362 --> 00:16:30.507
This act authorizes the removal

299
00:16:30.531 --> 00:16:33.677
of the Tribe of the Great and Little Osage
from Kansas…

300
00:16:33.701 --> 00:16:37.555
[William translating into Osage]

301
00:16:37.579 --> 00:16:41.351
…to a new and permanent home
in Indian territory.

302
00:16:41.375 --> 00:16:46.648
-[William translating into Osage]
-[chiefs murmuring in Osage]

303
00:16:46.672 --> 00:16:49.359
The Kansas lands will be purchased
for $1.25 an acre.

304
00:16:49.383 --> 00:16:51.802
[William translating into Osage]

305
00:16:52.386 --> 00:16:56.992
Those funds will then be used to secure
individual allotments for all Osage

306
00:16:57.016 --> 00:16:59.035
in lands formerly held by the Cherokee.

307
00:16:59.059 --> 00:17:01.079
[William translating into Osage]

308
00:17:01.103 --> 00:17:04.148
[chiefs murmuring unhappily in Osage]

309
00:17:05.107 --> 00:17:08.294
Owning private land
will allow you to thrive.

310
00:17:08.318 --> 00:17:11.256
Manual labor.
if properly directed to agriculture.

311
00:17:11.280 --> 00:17:13.133
will create a future for your families.

312
00:17:13.157 --> 00:17:17.595
[in Osage] We're warriors! Not farmers!

313
00:17:17.619 --> 00:17:21.808
Without the buffalo hunt. we will starve.

314
00:17:21.832 --> 00:17:25.603
Sit down. cousin. Let him speak.

315
00:17:25.627 --> 00:17:29.482
His words are lies.
They promised protection.

316
00:17:29.506 --> 00:17:36.138
yet they allow more and more
of these people to take our land.

317
00:17:38.390 --> 00:17:39.510
[Governor Joe clears throat]

318
00:17:40.059 --> 00:17:41.226
Sit down.

319
00:17:50.861 --> 00:17:52.505
[in English] Let's continue.

320
00:17:52.529 --> 00:17:54.531
[men murmuring in Osage]

321
00:17:57.159 --> 00:18:00.597
-It's absolutely transformed.
-[Caroline chuckles]

322
00:18:00.621 --> 00:18:03.582
-All we need now is the guest of honor.
-Yeah.

323
00:18:04.083 --> 00:18:06.603
Caroline. you saved my life.

324
00:18:06.627 --> 00:18:08.063
Oh. don't be silly.

325
00:18:08.087 --> 00:18:09.254
No. I mean it.

326
00:18:10.714 --> 00:18:13.759
It wasn't right.
the way Jemma treated Miss Henderson.

327
00:18:14.468 --> 00:18:17.238
I should have said something.
but too much time passed.

328
00:18:17.262 --> 00:18:19.765
and I missed my chance.
and I said nothing.

329
00:18:20.349 --> 00:18:21.349
Forgive me.

330
00:18:22.684 --> 00:18:24.103
-Oh my.
-[Jemma] Hm.

331
00:18:25.979 --> 00:18:27.481
You've outdone yourselves.

332
00:18:27.981 --> 00:18:30.400
I wanted to make sure
you had a proper welcome.

333
00:18:31.860 --> 00:18:34.488
I'm afraid the day
didn't start out quite so well.

334
00:18:35.322 --> 00:18:38.051
but Caroline Ingalls came to our rescue.

335
00:18:38.075 --> 00:18:39.803
This is all her doing.

336
00:18:39.827 --> 00:18:41.846
I'm sure everyone pitched in.

337
00:18:41.870 --> 00:18:44.140
-They did.
-[Reverend] Mmm.

338
00:18:44.164 --> 00:18:45.164
Well.

339
00:18:46.041 --> 00:18:47.709
it's absolutely magical.

340
00:18:48.460 --> 00:18:51.630
Let's get a plate.
and you'll tell me all about yourself.

341
00:18:58.512 --> 00:19:00.514
[both laughing]

342
00:19:02.057 --> 00:19:04.226
[horse whinnies]

343
00:19:06.270 --> 00:19:08.540
-How much candy's in here?
-Open it.

344
00:19:08.564 --> 00:19:09.565
[Good Eagle chuckles]

345
00:19:13.735 --> 00:19:16.589
Whenever we play at the creek.
I see you picking up pebbles.

346
00:19:16.613 --> 00:19:18.550
You like the round. bright ones.

347
00:19:18.574 --> 00:19:21.761
So after the snow melted. I started
looking for the prettiest pebbles

348
00:19:21.785 --> 00:19:22.911
and saving them for you.

349
00:19:26.540 --> 00:19:27.875
You don't like them?

350
00:19:28.667 --> 00:19:29.667
I do.

351
00:19:31.879 --> 00:19:35.215
There's another treasure.
a better treasure. We can go get that one.

352
00:19:36.717 --> 00:19:38.570
Let's go somewhere else first.

353
00:19:38.594 --> 00:19:40.596
[emotional music playing]

354
00:19:59.489 --> 00:20:00.908
Is everything all right?

355
00:20:04.203 --> 00:20:06.014
How long have my parents been in debt?

356
00:20:06.038 --> 00:20:07.140
[music fades]

357
00:20:07.164 --> 00:20:10.834
Emily and Samuel know they're good for it.
once their crop goes to market.

358
00:20:11.335 --> 00:20:13.086
Please don't tell Emily I let you see.

359
00:20:14.922 --> 00:20:17.233
-What was it for?
-[Caleb] Ordinary things.

360
00:20:17.257 --> 00:20:20.028
Eggs. candles. thread for your embroidery…

361
00:20:20.052 --> 00:20:22.763
Everyone's in debt. Mary.
You saw the book.

362
00:20:23.555 --> 00:20:24.449
I know.

363
00:20:24.473 --> 00:20:26.475
[melancholy music playing]

364
00:20:32.189 --> 00:20:33.189
[Mary] It's just…

365
00:20:33.857 --> 00:20:37.527
Pa said everything was fine.
even when I asked.

366
00:20:39.863 --> 00:20:40.863
He lied to me.

367
00:20:45.661 --> 00:20:47.913
Your parents took on debt to survive.

368
00:20:49.498 --> 00:20:50.916
to keep you together.

369
00:20:52.709 --> 00:20:53.794
They love you.

370
00:20:54.586 --> 00:20:56.505
And they just wanna protect you.

371
00:20:59.341 --> 00:21:00.968
I wish I had a family like that.

372
00:21:02.844 --> 00:21:04.096
You have Emily.

373
00:21:06.640 --> 00:21:07.640
I know.

374
00:21:12.020 --> 00:21:13.272
And I have you.

375
00:21:14.564 --> 00:21:16.566
[music swells]

376
00:21:23.031 --> 00:21:24.283
-[door opens]
-[both gasp]

377
00:21:30.497 --> 00:21:31.915
Made you a plate. Caleb.

378
00:21:33.625 --> 00:21:34.710
You too. Mary.

379
00:21:35.544 --> 00:21:36.878
-Thank you.
-[Emily] Mm-hm.

380
00:21:42.301 --> 00:21:43.301
[Mary laughs]

381
00:21:44.177 --> 00:21:46.179
[somber music playing]

382
00:21:54.313 --> 00:21:56.023
[indistinct chatter in Osage]

383
00:21:59.651 --> 00:22:00.819
[speaking Osage]

384
00:22:01.528 --> 00:22:03.006
[in English] Not Afraid of Pawnees.

385
00:22:03.030 --> 00:22:06.867
Governor of the Big Hills Band.
will you rise and hold the feather?

386
00:22:13.832 --> 00:22:15.834
[indistinct chatter in Osage]

387
00:22:28.472 --> 00:22:30.474
[men murmuring in Osage]

388
00:22:31.516 --> 00:22:35.062
[speaking Osage]

389
00:22:39.274 --> 00:22:42.795
[in English] This is the land
where our fathers died.

390
00:22:42.819 --> 00:22:43.921
[speaking Osage]

391
00:22:43.945 --> 00:22:48.033
This is the land where they are buried.
One day. we will face them again.

392
00:22:48.617 --> 00:22:50.869
[Governor Joe speaking Osage]

393
00:22:56.792 --> 00:22:59.252
[in English] They will ask us
a simple question.

394
00:23:00.629 --> 00:23:02.732
What future did we leave to our children?

395
00:23:02.756 --> 00:23:05.109
[Governor Joe continues in Osage]

396
00:23:05.133 --> 00:23:07.570
[William] Did we keep the ways
our grandparents gave us alive

397
00:23:07.594 --> 00:23:08.863
for them to carry?

398
00:23:08.887 --> 00:23:11.032
[speaking Osage]

399
00:23:11.056 --> 00:23:13.618
[in English] When I face my father.
this will be my answer.

400
00:23:13.642 --> 00:23:16.812
[men chattering in Osage]

401
00:23:24.694 --> 00:23:27.072
[music intensifies. stops]

402
00:23:28.824 --> 00:23:31.284
-[Osage men cheering]
-[music resumes]

403
00:23:45.966 --> 00:23:47.467
Guess the deal wasn't fair after all.

404
00:23:48.802 --> 00:23:50.220
[Eli] What's happening?

405
00:23:50.762 --> 00:23:53.408
Where's he going? What's happening?!

406
00:23:53.432 --> 00:23:55.434
[chattering in Osage continues]

407
00:23:57.602 --> 00:23:58.704
[music fades]

408
00:23:58.728 --> 00:24:01.273
[in English] Jemma's told me
a great deal about this town.

409
00:24:02.149 --> 00:24:03.817
mostly her contributions.

410
00:24:04.943 --> 00:24:09.448
I have a feeling she left some things out.
Who the real leaders are. for instance.

411
00:24:10.198 --> 00:24:12.593
-Like yourself.
-Oh. I'm not a leader.

412
00:24:12.617 --> 00:24:15.912
I doubt that very much.
The women here clearly look up to you.

413
00:24:17.330 --> 00:24:20.768
So. tell me about your vision
for this town.

414
00:24:20.792 --> 00:24:22.669
-My vision?
-Yes.

415
00:24:23.670 --> 00:24:25.630
A place where hard work is rewarded.

416
00:24:26.131 --> 00:24:29.426
Place where everyone
can become who they're meant to be.

417
00:24:30.844 --> 00:24:32.363
Place where children can be educated

418
00:24:32.387 --> 00:24:34.490
as they were
in the cities and towns we left behind.

419
00:24:34.514 --> 00:24:36.284
Education's important to you.

420
00:24:36.308 --> 00:24:37.410
[Caroline] I was a teacher.

421
00:24:37.434 --> 00:24:39.936
I saw how it opened up
the world for children.

422
00:24:42.189 --> 00:24:43.189
I loved it.

423
00:24:44.983 --> 00:24:48.153
I'll tell you what.
I only need this church on Sundays.

424
00:24:48.653 --> 00:24:51.174
Rest of the week.
these four walls could be yours.

425
00:24:51.198 --> 00:24:54.552
Oh. no. I couldn't.
It's not a married woman's place to teach.

426
00:24:54.576 --> 00:24:58.580
This is the West. Mrs. Ingalls.
What use do we have for the old rules?

427
00:25:02.584 --> 00:25:05.480
Hey. Scott. You live near that Osage camp.

428
00:25:05.504 --> 00:25:06.755
They finish up yet?

429
00:25:07.255 --> 00:25:10.067
Hardly. The whole thing
was chaos when I passed through.

430
00:25:10.091 --> 00:25:10.985
What do you mean?

431
00:25:11.009 --> 00:25:13.571
One of the chiefs walked out.
refused to sign.

432
00:25:13.595 --> 00:25:14.906
[tense music playing]

433
00:25:14.930 --> 00:25:16.610
I took the long way around to steer clear.

434
00:25:17.724 --> 00:25:18.850
Say again?

435
00:25:20.435 --> 00:25:21.496
What happens now?

436
00:25:21.520 --> 00:25:23.522
I give him some space.

437
00:25:25.273 --> 00:25:27.108
then I try to put things back together.

438
00:25:28.193 --> 00:25:30.946
-And what does that look like?
-I'm not sure.

439
00:25:32.239 --> 00:25:35.301
Mitchell. take me to that chief.

440
00:25:35.325 --> 00:25:38.179
He needs to know
if he doesn't finish this today.

441
00:25:38.203 --> 00:25:41.373
the army will gladly
finish this next week.

442
00:25:42.374 --> 00:25:45.293
-You're talking about war?
-I'm talking about common sense.

443
00:25:46.211 --> 00:25:48.064
This was all supposed to be a formality.

444
00:25:48.088 --> 00:25:50.441
There's no such thing as a formality

445
00:25:50.465 --> 00:25:52.735
when it comes to the future
of an entire people.

446
00:25:52.759 --> 00:25:54.237
[exhales angrily]

447
00:25:54.261 --> 00:25:57.073
This is your future
on the line too. Ingalls.

448
00:25:57.097 --> 00:26:00.892
This is their home. They have the right
to decide whether or not they stay or go.

449
00:26:02.018 --> 00:26:03.812
Not you. Not me.

450
00:26:04.729 --> 00:26:05.772
Not the railroad.

451
00:26:06.898 --> 00:26:07.899
[scoffs]

452
00:26:13.822 --> 00:26:16.366
-What's going on over there?
-[Lacey] Nothing good.

453
00:26:16.866 --> 00:26:19.804
Lots of talk of ammunition and guns.

454
00:26:19.828 --> 00:26:23.415
-There's no need to be dramatic.
-I assure you she's not.

455
00:26:24.040 --> 00:26:27.645
I know what fear looks like in men.
and I see it in those faces.

456
00:26:27.669 --> 00:26:30.648
She's right. They're spoiling for a fight.

457
00:26:30.672 --> 00:26:32.757
[indistinct chatter]

458
00:26:33.341 --> 00:26:37.220
Reverend. words from you
will surely put an end to such talk.

459
00:26:44.394 --> 00:26:46.146
[Reverend] Ladies and gentlemen.

460
00:26:46.896 --> 00:26:49.274
thank you for the warm welcome.

461
00:26:49.816 --> 00:26:52.753
I've only been here a day.
but I have seen the foundations

462
00:26:52.777 --> 00:26:54.613
upon which this town is built.

463
00:26:55.155 --> 00:26:56.757
-Kindness.
-[music fades]

464
00:26:56.781 --> 00:26:57.781
Generosity.

465
00:26:58.241 --> 00:27:00.595
Gingersnaps and blackberry cobblers.

466
00:27:00.619 --> 00:27:02.203
[townspeople laugh]

467
00:27:03.872 --> 00:27:07.626
But I also hear of another block
upon which we stand.

468
00:27:08.752 --> 00:27:11.880
Fear. Fear is an unstable foundation.

469
00:27:12.380 --> 00:27:16.509
It clouds goodwill
the way ink clouds spring water.

470
00:27:17.260 --> 00:27:20.031
I know there's a great deal
of uncertainty at the moment.

471
00:27:20.055 --> 00:27:23.618
and I implore you to face it
with the virtue of restraint.

472
00:27:23.642 --> 00:27:26.102
[crowd murmuring]

473
00:27:27.479 --> 00:27:30.291
And. uh. that goes for the cobbler too.

474
00:27:30.315 --> 00:27:32.025
[laughing]

475
00:27:34.402 --> 00:27:36.172
[Russell] All due respect. Reverend.

476
00:27:36.196 --> 00:27:38.823
You don't know
a damn thing about Independence.

477
00:27:39.658 --> 00:27:43.387
Save your sermons for Sundays.
Leave town business to us.

478
00:27:43.411 --> 00:27:44.871
[tense music playing]

479
00:27:52.837 --> 00:27:55.298
I don't even remember
what brought me to this place.

480
00:27:56.800 --> 00:27:58.385
When the war was over.

481
00:27:59.177 --> 00:28:00.529
I started runnin'…

482
00:28:00.553 --> 00:28:01.781
[music fades]

483
00:28:01.805 --> 00:28:02.805
…for years.

484
00:28:05.475 --> 00:28:08.687
Then one day. I just woke up here.

485
00:28:11.815 --> 00:28:13.108
It was so beautiful.

486
00:28:16.444 --> 00:28:18.613
And I knew it wasn't mine. but I loved it.

487
00:28:20.615 --> 00:28:22.158
So I stopped runnin'.

488
00:28:23.159 --> 00:28:28.289
After Mitchell's daughter passed.
I'd sit up with him all night.

489
00:28:29.582 --> 00:28:33.294
Wouldn't say anything.
We'd just stare up at the stars.

490
00:28:36.464 --> 00:28:39.467
If I was the Osage.
I would never give this land up.

491
00:28:40.427 --> 00:28:41.553
not one inch.

492
00:28:43.179 --> 00:28:45.366
I'm not sure they have
a choice at this point.

493
00:28:45.390 --> 00:28:47.767
No. they don't.

494
00:28:49.310 --> 00:28:50.645
I mean. not a real one.

495
00:28:54.482 --> 00:28:56.109
We're gonna have to live with that.

496
00:28:59.070 --> 00:29:01.072
[melancholy music playing]

497
00:29:06.828 --> 00:29:08.955
[Good Eagle] Persimmons were
Julia's favorite.

498
00:29:11.332 --> 00:29:14.002
She'd eat so many.
she'd make herself sick.

499
00:29:15.003 --> 00:29:17.839
Even when Mama warned her.
she couldn't stop herself.

500
00:29:22.302 --> 00:29:24.220
Julia left us in the summer.

501
00:29:26.931 --> 00:29:29.976
That fall. the trees
near our house didn't have any fruit.

502
00:29:31.144 --> 00:29:33.146
Think they missed her as much as I did.

503
00:29:35.231 --> 00:29:36.441
But then I saw this one.

504
00:29:38.193 --> 00:29:41.196
This one had
ten trees' worth of persimmons.

505
00:29:41.946 --> 00:29:44.908
And I knew it was a sign from Julia

506
00:29:46.075 --> 00:29:47.619
that she'd always be with me.

507
00:29:51.623 --> 00:29:53.625
[Laura] That's why you collect stones.

508
00:29:55.877 --> 00:29:57.045
They're for Julia.

509
00:30:00.256 --> 00:30:01.925
She was my best friend.

510
00:30:07.555 --> 00:30:08.555
Do you wanna help?

511
00:30:13.770 --> 00:30:15.522
[stones rattle]

512
00:30:26.157 --> 00:30:28.159
[indistinct chatter in Osage]

513
00:30:29.536 --> 00:30:32.223
[in English] May we talk?
Without the others?

514
00:30:32.247 --> 00:30:34.541
-[horse whinnies]
-[music fades]

515
00:30:35.124 --> 00:30:36.960
I know you speak English.

516
00:30:37.877 --> 00:30:41.089
Father Schoenmaker said you were
one of the brightest students he ever had.

517
00:30:50.223 --> 00:30:54.185
Never negotiate in the tongue
of those who lie with such ease.

518
00:30:54.769 --> 00:30:56.771
Yes. it's hard to trust them.

519
00:30:58.231 --> 00:31:00.108
But if you don't sign.

520
00:31:00.650 --> 00:31:02.336
we both know how that ends.

521
00:31:02.360 --> 00:31:05.446
And if we do sign. what can we expect?

522
00:31:05.947 --> 00:31:07.842
More broken promises?

523
00:31:07.866 --> 00:31:11.303
Policies that favor
the politicians and the railroad?

524
00:31:11.327 --> 00:31:16.416
Policies that makes us all farmers.
toiling in the dirt.

525
00:31:16.916 --> 00:31:20.378
each family alone
on their little parcel of land?

526
00:31:21.087 --> 00:31:23.691
-But we will own that land.
-[Governor Joe] What do you mean. "we"?

527
00:31:23.715 --> 00:31:26.861
I hear you're one of those
that plans to stay.

528
00:31:26.885 --> 00:31:28.177
I'm still Osage.

529
00:31:28.761 --> 00:31:30.614
And I would hope by now you understand

530
00:31:30.638 --> 00:31:34.410
that I'm here to help you get everything
that you need from this deal.

531
00:31:34.434 --> 00:31:36.495
You don't even know what that is.

532
00:31:36.519 --> 00:31:37.496
Then tell me.

533
00:31:37.520 --> 00:31:39.188
Our dignity.

534
00:31:42.859 --> 00:31:44.569
If I can help you keep that.

535
00:31:45.820 --> 00:31:46.905
will you sign?

536
00:31:51.117 --> 00:31:53.345
<i>Our leaders need two amendments.</i>

537
00:31:53.369 --> 00:31:56.348
First. the Osage must be permitted

538
00:31:56.372 --> 00:31:59.602
to hunt the buffalo beyond the borders
of their new territory.

539
00:31:59.626 --> 00:32:01.628
[Osage murmuring in agreement]

540
00:32:02.921 --> 00:32:03.921
And the second?

541
00:32:04.839 --> 00:32:09.302
This new land
will not be allotted individually.

542
00:32:10.345 --> 00:32:13.681
It will be held by the Osage communally.

543
00:32:14.265 --> 00:32:16.585
-As a tribe. as a people.
-[Osage murmuring in agreement]

544
00:32:23.691 --> 00:32:25.377
[clears throat softly]

545
00:32:25.401 --> 00:32:26.962
Negotiations are over.

546
00:32:26.986 --> 00:32:28.947
[indistinct chatter in Osage]

547
00:32:30.573 --> 00:32:33.218
[melancholy music playing]

548
00:32:33.242 --> 00:32:34.619
[chatter continues]

549
00:32:41.960 --> 00:32:47.382
We were once the largest.
most powerful nation on this continent.

550
00:32:47.882 --> 00:32:53.179
But treaty after treaty
has shrunken our land and our numbers

551
00:32:54.055 --> 00:32:55.264
but not our pride.

552
00:32:58.685 --> 00:32:59.936
Mr. Gibson.

553
00:33:00.645 --> 00:33:03.666
the Osage must stay together…

554
00:33:03.690 --> 00:33:06.025
[murmurs of agreement]

555
00:33:11.906 --> 00:33:13.509
…for our children's future.

556
00:33:13.533 --> 00:33:15.952
[murmurs of agreement]

557
00:33:17.954 --> 00:33:20.331
I don't have the authority
to make those changes.

558
00:33:22.375 --> 00:33:24.127
I don't believe that to be true.

559
00:33:24.627 --> 00:33:27.213
[rousing music playing]

560
00:33:29.841 --> 00:33:31.819
-Caroline! Where are you going?
-[music fades]

561
00:33:31.843 --> 00:33:34.613
Russell Kind moved
his little grievance circle to the hotel.

562
00:33:34.637 --> 00:33:35.572
[Jemma] I know that.

563
00:33:35.596 --> 00:33:39.118
I just asked Dr. Tann to ride out for Eli.
He'll know how to put a stop to all this.

564
00:33:39.142 --> 00:33:41.894
-I'm not gonna wait around to find out.
-[Mary] Ma?

565
00:33:44.355 --> 00:33:45.565
What's happening?

566
00:33:46.399 --> 00:33:48.627
I'm gonna talk some men out of
doing something stupid.

567
00:33:48.651 --> 00:33:51.738
-They're not going to listen to a woman.
-I guess we'll see.

568
00:33:52.238 --> 00:33:55.533
[Russell] The Osage aren't fools.
They know what refusing to sign means.

569
00:33:56.117 --> 00:33:58.846
And if they ride on us.
this town's got no defense.

570
00:33:58.870 --> 00:34:00.264
[Bronson] It'd be a turkey shoot.

571
00:34:00.288 --> 00:34:03.767
I say we gather up all the weapons
and ammunition we can. and we ride on them

572
00:34:03.791 --> 00:34:05.269
as soon as possible.

573
00:34:05.293 --> 00:34:07.170
There are children in that village.

574
00:34:09.464 --> 00:34:12.425
-Families.
-And what about our children and families?

575
00:34:13.134 --> 00:34:14.528
What about yours?

576
00:34:14.552 --> 00:34:15.988
[drums sounding]

577
00:34:16.012 --> 00:34:18.824
You hear those drums starting up again?
That means war!

578
00:34:18.848 --> 00:34:21.243
That's a load of dust.
You don't know what it means.

579
00:34:21.267 --> 00:34:23.120
Mrs. Ingalls. come on now.

580
00:34:23.144 --> 00:34:25.414
We need to show 'em
we won't be pushed around.

581
00:34:25.438 --> 00:34:26.939
[Russell] Don't pay her any mind.

582
00:34:27.690 --> 00:34:29.293
She's in too deep.

583
00:34:29.317 --> 00:34:31.903
I'm in deep enough
to know they're good people.

584
00:34:32.862 --> 00:34:35.340
trying to make a life and a future.
just like you.

585
00:34:35.364 --> 00:34:37.366
[unsettling music playing]

586
00:34:37.909 --> 00:34:39.762
They are nothin' like me.

587
00:34:39.786 --> 00:34:41.788
I came here with those same ideas.

588
00:34:43.289 --> 00:34:46.250
I thought I knew so much of the world.
but I was wrong.

589
00:34:47.710 --> 00:34:48.961
And so are you.

590
00:34:50.296 --> 00:34:54.401
If you drag this town to war.
every drop of blood will be on your hands.

591
00:34:54.425 --> 00:34:56.385
[Russell chuckles]

592
00:34:58.221 --> 00:35:00.389
-I don't want a war.
-[Russell] It's not a war.

593
00:35:01.432 --> 00:35:02.517
It's self-defense.

594
00:35:03.392 --> 00:35:07.289
Now. anyone who's got an ounce of courage.
you take up your weapons. you follow me.

595
00:35:07.313 --> 00:35:09.315
[men murmur]

596
00:35:12.777 --> 00:35:13.778
It's done.

597
00:35:14.487 --> 00:35:15.488
They signed.

598
00:35:16.280 --> 00:35:19.534
The government agreed to their terms.
The Osage are selling the land.

599
00:35:20.034 --> 00:35:22.036
[melancholy music playing]

600
00:35:30.878 --> 00:35:32.880
[indistinct chatter]

601
00:35:43.224 --> 00:35:45.536
[man] Thank you. That's why I'm here.

602
00:35:45.560 --> 00:35:47.329
[Good Eagle] The last treasure's in here.

603
00:35:47.353 --> 00:35:50.040
[Laura] It's all right.
We don't need to finish.

604
00:35:50.064 --> 00:35:52.567
I want to. It's my birthday.

605
00:35:59.740 --> 00:36:02.261
"Dear Good Eagle. happy birthday."

606
00:36:02.285 --> 00:36:06.807
"I've never known anybody
as smart or funny or brave as you."

607
00:36:06.831 --> 00:36:09.000
"I wish I could be more like you."

608
00:36:09.917 --> 00:36:12.461
"And I hope we can be
best friends forever."

609
00:36:14.046 --> 00:36:16.674
You already have a best friend.
I shouldn't have asked.

610
00:36:19.135 --> 00:36:20.428
I could have another one.

611
00:36:22.471 --> 00:36:23.681
Julia wouldn't mind.

612
00:36:29.228 --> 00:36:30.228
So.

613
00:36:31.063 --> 00:36:32.523
what was the surprise?

614
00:36:33.274 --> 00:36:36.003
Well. Laura and I…

615
00:36:36.027 --> 00:36:37.987
[music fades]

616
00:36:38.821 --> 00:36:40.299
…searched for treasure.

617
00:36:40.323 --> 00:36:41.758
[White Sun gasps softly]

618
00:36:41.782 --> 00:36:43.910
This looks like a lot of work.

619
00:36:45.036 --> 00:36:46.329
Did they sign the treaty. Mama?

620
00:36:48.331 --> 00:36:49.457
They did.

621
00:36:51.459 --> 00:36:52.585
What happens now?

622
00:36:53.586 --> 00:36:57.006
I don't know. but change is coming.

623
00:36:57.882 --> 00:37:00.218
I wish we could all stay here together.

624
00:37:01.677 --> 00:37:03.780
[sad music playing]

625
00:37:03.804 --> 00:37:05.431
I wish no one had to leave.

626
00:37:15.066 --> 00:37:17.360
Do you know where the Osage come from?

627
00:37:21.364 --> 00:37:24.659
Our <i>Wa-zha-zhe</i> ancestors

628
00:37:25.701 --> 00:37:28.579
came to Earth
from the upper world and the stars.

629
00:37:29.413 --> 00:37:32.917
When they landed.
they traveled together looking for a home.

630
00:37:33.417 --> 00:37:34.794
Even when they found one.

631
00:37:35.294 --> 00:37:37.588
things would happen
that led them to move to a new one.

632
00:37:38.464 --> 00:37:43.094
There was always more to see.
to learn. to feel.

633
00:37:43.594 --> 00:37:45.554
We carry those memories in us.

634
00:37:46.931 --> 00:37:48.641
That is why we tell stories.

635
00:37:49.141 --> 00:37:51.894
to remember that moving and changing

636
00:37:52.395 --> 00:37:55.064
brings us closer
to understanding <i>Wah'Kon-Tah…</i>

637
00:37:57.191 --> 00:37:58.276
The Great Mystery.

638
00:38:04.365 --> 00:38:06.367
[music intensifies]

639
00:38:16.377 --> 00:38:17.562
[music fades]

640
00:38:17.586 --> 00:38:20.339
I wanted to believe
that everything was being handled fairly.

641
00:38:20.923 --> 00:38:23.360
that everyone was getting
what they wanted.

642
00:38:23.384 --> 00:38:25.386
[indistinct chatter]

643
00:38:26.137 --> 00:38:28.723
Because I could only think
of my own family.

644
00:38:29.807 --> 00:38:31.642
the life I wanted them to have.

645
00:38:35.187 --> 00:38:37.481
I willed myself not to see the truth.

646
00:38:38.566 --> 00:38:39.734
and for that. I'm sorry.

647
00:38:42.570 --> 00:38:45.781
[footsteps approaching]

648
00:38:46.782 --> 00:38:49.744
[speaking Osage]

649
00:39:15.311 --> 00:39:16.437
What did he say?

650
00:39:17.313 --> 00:39:19.315
[melancholy music playing]

651
00:39:21.650 --> 00:39:22.693
He says…

652
00:39:25.571 --> 00:39:27.198
"I hope you'll listen tomorrow."

653
00:39:28.199 --> 00:39:29.199
"At dawn.

654
00:39:30.159 --> 00:39:32.411
you will hear
our people's song of mourning."

655
00:39:33.871 --> 00:39:37.083
"We will be praying
to <i>Wah'Kon-Tah</i> to take pity on us."

656
00:39:38.459 --> 00:39:40.419
"Leaving this land means

657
00:39:41.212 --> 00:39:45.508
we leave our ancestors. our history.
and a part of ourselves behind."

658
00:40:00.564 --> 00:40:01.564
[William sighs]

659
00:40:04.652 --> 00:40:08.906
[Mary. Laura]
<i>♪ And then I will tell to you. darling ♪</i>

660
00:40:09.490 --> 00:40:13.619
<i>♪ All the love I have cherished so long ♪</i>

661
00:40:14.453 --> 00:40:18.999
<i>♪ If you will but meet me at evening ♪</i>

662
00:40:19.500 --> 00:40:23.879
<i>♪ When you hear
The first whip-poor-will's song ♪</i>

663
00:40:26.966 --> 00:40:28.652
[music fades]

664
00:40:28.676 --> 00:40:30.904
The railroad made all those flyers.
didn't they?

665
00:40:30.928 --> 00:40:31.928
[Eli sighs]

666
00:40:32.805 --> 00:40:33.889
[Charles] You used us

667
00:40:34.807 --> 00:40:36.183
to force the Osage out.

668
00:40:37.518 --> 00:40:40.271
The company has a vision of our future.

669
00:40:41.313 --> 00:40:44.358
a good vision. one of wealth and progress.

670
00:40:45.192 --> 00:40:47.570
You're part of that vision. Ingalls.

671
00:40:48.070 --> 00:40:49.947
Be grateful. [inhales sharply]

672
00:40:51.157 --> 00:40:52.551
[clears throat]

673
00:40:52.575 --> 00:40:54.702
[Carrie cooing]

674
00:40:56.787 --> 00:40:58.789
[bright music playing]

675
00:40:59.915 --> 00:41:00.916
Ready to go home?

676
00:41:06.213 --> 00:41:08.215
[Carrie cooing]

677
00:41:10.259 --> 00:41:11.469
[chuckles softly]

678
00:41:21.479 --> 00:41:22.646
[knocking on door]

679
00:41:23.647 --> 00:41:24.940
[bell dinging]

680
00:41:25.900 --> 00:41:27.359
[Emily laughs]

681
00:41:28.652 --> 00:41:29.796
[Dr. Tann laughs]

682
00:41:29.820 --> 00:41:32.466
-Thank you.
-Whoa. what's all this?

683
00:41:32.490 --> 00:41:35.242
Well. I thought supper
should be special tonight.

684
00:41:35.743 --> 00:41:38.412
-Every supper is special with you.
-[Emily chuckles]

685
00:41:40.915 --> 00:41:41.975
[Emily clears throat]

686
00:41:41.999 --> 00:41:44.001
[music fades]

687
00:41:45.711 --> 00:41:46.711
Well.

688
00:41:48.088 --> 00:41:51.592
the thing is. we've been doing this
for a while now. George.

689
00:41:52.092 --> 00:41:54.803
and even though
I enjoy our evenings together. we…

690
00:41:56.013 --> 00:41:57.765
We can't go on like this forever.

691
00:41:58.891 --> 00:41:59.975
Oh?

692
00:42:06.232 --> 00:42:08.335
[Dr. Tann takes a deep breath]

693
00:42:08.359 --> 00:42:12.988
I know you had another life
before you came here.

694
00:42:14.198 --> 00:42:18.661
But. um. I'd very much like to be a part
of the life you're living right now…

695
00:42:21.497 --> 00:42:23.916
Or the life
you'll be living in the future…

696
00:42:26.502 --> 00:42:27.586
If you'll have me.

697
00:42:30.881 --> 00:42:31.881
[Emily laughs]

698
00:42:32.550 --> 00:42:35.529
Well. I… I hope
you don't think me bold as brass.

699
00:42:35.553 --> 00:42:37.555
but that's exactly what I am sometimes.

700
00:42:41.267 --> 00:42:42.410
[sighs softly]

701
00:42:42.434 --> 00:42:43.644
I haven't been

702
00:42:44.812 --> 00:42:46.397
completely honest with ya.

703
00:42:52.778 --> 00:42:53.946
I'm still married.

704
00:42:54.863 --> 00:42:55.966
technically.

705
00:42:55.990 --> 00:42:57.992
[melancholy music playing]

706
00:43:04.290 --> 00:43:05.290
I'm sorry.

707
00:43:09.295 --> 00:43:10.296
I should've said.

708
00:43:17.011 --> 00:43:19.013
Yes. you should've.

709
00:44:07.895 --> 00:44:11.357
[breathing shakily]

710
00:44:21.700 --> 00:44:22.700
[music fades]

711
00:44:23.243 --> 00:44:24.870
How was the treasure hunt?

712
00:44:26.747 --> 00:44:28.165
I think it was worth it.

713
00:44:28.957 --> 00:44:30.751
-She seemed happy.
-[Mary] That's good.

714
00:44:31.251 --> 00:44:33.879
You've never done
anything that nice for me.

715
00:44:34.797 --> 00:44:36.048
Maybe next birthday I will.

716
00:44:37.049 --> 00:44:40.236
Something about <i>Alice in Wonderland</i>?

717
00:44:40.260 --> 00:44:41.988
Maybe a tea party?

718
00:44:42.012 --> 00:44:43.597
[both giggle]

719
00:44:44.473 --> 00:44:45.474
How was your day?

720
00:44:47.726 --> 00:44:48.662
Confusing.

721
00:44:48.686 --> 00:44:49.895
What do you mean?

722
00:44:50.688 --> 00:44:51.688
[inhales deeply]

723
00:44:53.148 --> 00:44:54.900
I'll tell you about it in the morning.

724
00:44:59.655 --> 00:45:00.698
[Mary sighs]

725
00:45:04.076 --> 00:45:07.204
I heard you made Russell Kind
shrivel up like a plucked weed.

726
00:45:07.913 --> 00:45:09.182
Not exactly.

727
00:45:09.206 --> 00:45:11.500
[breathes deeply]

728
00:45:12.042 --> 00:45:13.419
But maybe a little.

729
00:45:16.046 --> 00:45:17.506
I'm sorry I missed it.

730
00:45:20.300 --> 00:45:23.178
The whole time
we were making the trip from Wisconsin.

731
00:45:23.846 --> 00:45:26.014
I kept thinking
about who we'd become out here.

732
00:45:28.892 --> 00:45:30.477
what kind of people we'd be.

733
00:45:32.271 --> 00:45:34.815
Now I can hardly imagine
the people we were.

734
00:45:39.027 --> 00:45:41.196
I can hardly imagine not being here.

735
00:45:42.531 --> 00:45:43.574
Is that a good thing?

736
00:45:50.038 --> 00:45:51.999
It's everything we wanted. isn't it?

737
00:46:12.060 --> 00:46:13.562
[drums sounding in the distance]

738
00:46:15.522 --> 00:46:17.524
[singing in Osage]

739
00:46:24.156 --> 00:46:26.158
[singing and drumming continues]

740
00:46:48.847 --> 00:46:50.849
[singing and drumming continues]

741
00:47:17.417 --> 00:47:19.419
[singing and drumming continues]

742
00:47:44.695 --> 00:47:46.697
[singing and drumming continues]

743
00:48:08.844 --> 00:48:10.846
[singing and drumming continues]

744
00:49:00.354 --> 00:49:01.354
[music ends]

745
00:49:03.357 --> 00:49:05.359
[closing theme music playing]

746
00:49:34.179 --> 00:49:35.347
[music ends]
